    "summary": "Polished obsidian mirrors discovered at [[event:11|Catalhoyuk]] in Anatolia, dating to approximately 6200–6000 BCE, represent the earliest known examples of manufactured reflective surfaces. Obsidian — a volcanic glass prized throughout the Neolithic for its capacity to be knapped into extremely sharp edges — was also capable of being ground and polished to produce smooth, reflective surfaces. The mirrors found at Catalhoyuk are small, hand-held pieces that were apparently used for personal grooming or adornment.\n\nThe production of obsidian mirrors required considerable skill and access to high-quality raw material, which was traded across long distances in the Neolithic Near East. Their presence at Catalhoyuk suggests that self-presentation and bodily appearance were socially significant matters in this early settled community. These objects are the oldest known precursors to a technology — the manufactured mirror — that would become universal across human cultures.",
